We recommended management to undertake following courses of action:
Cause the refund by the contractors concerned of the equivalent cost of the underruns in their specific projects undertaken as computed above;

Closely monitor the scaling noted in the improvement of Kias Barangay Road near Old Dynamite Bodega at Barangay Virac, though these are considered minor.  Require the contractor to correct the same at his own expense, if they worsen within the one year defects liability period.  Also, require the contractor to seal with asphalt the transverse crack to prevent base saturation;

Ensure that contracts include provisions for liquidated damages pursuant to Section 68 of RA No. 9184 as well as contract time/duration for the project; and

Ensure that tarpaulin signboards of projects contain all the data/information required therein. Signboards with blank/incomplete project details shall be considered as non-compliant and the pertinent cost thereof be deducted from the project cost.

We recommended management the following:

Speed up the negotiations with Antamok Mines for the establishment of an engineered sanitary landfill in compliance with the Ecological Solid Waste Management Program under RA No. 9003;

Construct/provide security barrier/fence to deter illegal scavenging and scattering of the solid waste and prevent entrance of animals. Litter control including the use of litter fences and daily picking of litters should be provided in order to maintain cleanliness within the vicinity of the TRCA and prevent hazards to health and safety;


Continuously monitor the illegal dumping of solid waste along the roads and/or any prohibited places by providing the necessary garbage receptacles, signages and information and education dissemination; and

Consider providing the residents alternative means of waste containment during typhoons to prevent indiscriminate disposal which may pose hazards to health and safety of the public and the environment.

We have recommended management to –

Enforce the liquidation of all travel cash advances within the reglementary period of 30 days in accordance with the provisions of COA Circular No. 96-004;

Require that all cash advances be reported on as soon as the purpose for which it was given has been served and that all cash advances be fully liquidated at the end of the year in accordance with the provisions of COA Circular 97-002;

Enforce the return of any unexpended balance to the Cashier/Collecting Officer who will issue the necessary official receipt.

Direct the municipal accountant to monitor the liquidation of travel cash advances by deleting the name of the official or employee from subsequent payrolls, after due notice, until such time that the travel cash advance has been fully liquidated, if the official or employee concerned fails to liquidate the cash advance.

We have recommended management to –
Formulate the feasibility study for the equipment rental operations to establish the economic and social gains to be derived therefrom and as a performance measure in evaluating its sustainability;

Prepare the long-term, medium-term and annual business development plan for the economic enterprise; consider in the formulation of the business development plan the number of heavy equipment operators/drivers vis a vis the number of heavy equipment units based on previous market demand and a current market study for appropriate staffing requirements; and finalize the IRR to authorize the basis for the actions of the MEEDMO manager in the conduct of operations of the economic enterprise;

Prepare an annual budget for the economic enterprise to enable allocation of resources; submit the annual budget to the Local Sanggunian for authorization; and finalize a MOA with the SSC as regards the utilization and management of the SSC-owned units of heavy equipment; and

Conduct a regular evaluation on the social and financial performance of the economic enterprise for purposes of introducing new initiatives for operational improvement.

